No, clearly not. The creature only hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was nimble enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a scream as she narrowly avoided losing her grip on Thassalin's slick scales.
"HOW CAN WE KILL YOU?" Nyssi shouted.
"TARGET THEIR HEADS!"
"THAT'S GOING TO BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin hissed and drew a circle closer to the mountain, which he called home. The dark beast followed, but it became slightly panicked when it was hit by a burst of fire from behind. It hadn't realized it wasn't alone. It became even more terrified as Thassalin slowed down and then hurled its tail against its head, derailing its course.
Snarling and hissing, she shot upwards and spat into the air. Suddenly everything became dark as if the monster had sucked the light out of the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to withdraw. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before he finally tumbled into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and charged directly towards him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!" screamed Tenuk as he slid out of the cloud and began to circle, scanning the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What should we do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Nyssi struggled to her feet below. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing abilities were already taking effect. Unfortunately, that did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi exerted every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming and shrieking.
A daunting, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi on the ground, knocking her off balance. However, she noticed that the tail was swinging wildly and not attempting to hit her on purpose. The beast—what little of it Nyssi could see and hear—growled and swiped at the shadows she had created. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot rang out through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsing to the ground and lying motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, holding his rifle with heavy breathing.
"Probably... The craziest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon..." Kabel gasped for air. His eyes nearly glowed black, and a dark energy whirlwind surrounded his body. But as he continued to speak, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their usual yellow hue again.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. Everyone knew that Kayel possessed these peculiar shadow powers. He rarely used them because most found them eerie and quite intimidating. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could also employ these powers in any kind of darkness. And as Kayel behaved, he seemed to be rather surprised as well.
"The hell?" came out of Nyssi, or a more polite translation could be, "Are you okay?" came out of Nyssi. The exact translation depends on the context and tone that was intended. If "Bist du ok?" is meant as a greeting or check-in, the second option is more appropriate. If it conveys frustration or disbelief, the first option captures that sentiment better.
" Yes, I'm fine. I have killed something, and I'll be back to normal soon. " Kayel examined his work while Tenuk flew down and landed beside him, returning to his usual spasmodic form.
Now that the beast no longer moved, they could see better what it was. Its skin was pitch black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly stuck to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, slender claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell that thing was they were facing, something screamed and leaped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't make it to them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to skid to a halt at Nyssis feet. Nyssi wasn't taking any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without hesitation at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
"Ups…," murmled Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. "Uh, that was actually not intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the action," scolded Tenuk. "Where were you?"
" You all just left me standing there. I came as fast as I could... " Retvik sighed. "May I ask what those terrible creatures are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had rallied again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a little dazed, but not severely injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. ENTITIES THAT WERE SUPPOSED TO DIE OFF AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"Did you mean the terrible god-monster creature that we... helped to kill?" stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MAYBE THERE IS MORE. BUT I COULDN'T PUT IT IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, RIGHT?" Thassalin hobbled over to Kayel and patted his head. "MANY thanks, little one. YOU remind me of my old friend Arkadin. JUST not so murderous and not so capable of killing ENTIRE universes."
"Um... thank you... I think...", shrugged Kayel. "So, are we done here then?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few pictures of the now definitively dead monsters. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began cutting off one of the monster's horns. After that, she moved on to the next task. But just as Nyssi was finishing up, the monsters suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes in an instant. The same happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Also, this is practically and impractically convenient at the same time..." Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
